 needs (a bool occupies a byte; a small enum's discriminator fits in a byte). This headroom enables zero-cost migration-free schema changes: adding a unit variant that still fits the byte, appending struct fields under append-only encoding, widening fixed-width ints, provided variant order is preserved. The schema-layout schema exposes this headroom so derivation can skip zero-cost changes. Cap'n-Proto-style structural-compatibility discipline lives at the rkyv layer, not the NOTA text layer.|] Medium Medium Zero [rkyv zero-cost-migration nota capn-proto schema-layout])) (wrjl ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Decision [|Each persona contract carries an explicit content-addressable schema-layout schema in a NOTA-based language: its hash is its identity, so any edit changes the address (the version). The version-checking pipeline detects schema-address mismatches between code and stored data, walks the diff, and derives per-type migration operations (zero-cost variant extensions, append-only fields, structural migrations) baked into how types are written. MigrationIndex is the runtime decoder lookup; migration is per type; upgrade and downgrade are one compatibility-projection relation.|] Medium Medium Zero [schema-layout content-addressable nota migration-index version-projection])) (w1ss ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Decision [|Persona daemon schema migration uses in-process versioned reads: every record carries a schema-version tag, the daemon links every prior version's types and dispatches read-side on the tag, migrating older records on read (optionally rewriting), zero downtime per bump, applied to every triad. The per-type Migration trait carries a self-check/peer-coordination message knowing whether to consult the next-version daemon over an explicit version-handover protocol. Pilot record-shape changes are clean-break; production migration is operator work at cutover.|] Medium Medium Zero [schema-version-tag versioned-reads migration-trait daemon version-handover])) (9yxh ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Principle [|Schema namespace additions follow append-only discipline (new names added at the end of the available namespace) and enum slot planning minimizes database rewrites, so future enum-like compilation and upgrade logic stays compatible across upgrades.|] Medium Minimum Zero [append-only namespace enum-slot upgrade-compatibility])) (h2oa ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Constraint [Spirit releases carry schema-aware version numbers, and deployed Spirit versions are tagged before schema-migration planning.] Medium Minimum Zero [spirit version-number release-tag schema-migration])) (nm97 ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Decision [|Components have two schema categories. EXTERNAL schemas describe surfaces outside daemon runtime: wire contracts to other components (signal-vocabulary surviving the socket boundary) and database/storage contracts (state surviving process exit). INTERNAL schemas describe surfaces within runtime: actor message vocabularies and inter-actor channel contracts sharing process memory. Multiple schemas per component, each describing ONE channel; major actors get a schema. Internal-schema changes break neither database nor wire.|] High Medium Zero [external-schema internal-schema wire-contract storage-contract actor])) (mn3k ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Decision [Domain relations live as first-class, highly visible schema-declared vocabulary in a dedicated taxonomy schema surface, a new schema interface kind alongside the plane schemas, not an ad-hoc data file. The relation and expansion mechanism is reusable across components such as the mind.] Medium VeryHigh Zero [domain-relations taxonomy-schema mind schema-interface])) (uuh7 ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Principle [Components treat recompiling to change an enum set as trivial; zero-downtime upgrade is a design goal, so schema and enum changes are not a cost to design around] Medium High Zero [zero-downtime enum recompile schema-change])) (9pil ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Decision [Schema changes that affect stored data should be accepted through an upgrade testing pipeline: derive the new code, start a newly compiled daemon, test against a minimal specified database first, then test against a disposable copy of the live database before accepting the schema change.] Medium Minimum Zero [upgrade-testing schema-change daemon database])) (x2yz ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Clarification [|Per-repo data-type discipline (signal-X repos with versioned schema libraries) is what enables cross-version decoding and recovery|] Medium Minimum Zero [signal-x versioned-schema-library cross-version-decoding recovery])) (thi1 ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Principle [Schema and upgrade work should carry explicit provenance.] Medium Minimum Zero [schema upgrade provenance])) (rq3p ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Principle [When an old-version message is upgraded and accepted, the runtime should emit an observable event so introspection, routers, or agents can notify the source to upgrade its client schema.] Medium Minimum Zero [upgrade observable-event introspection client-schema])) (a9sq ([(Technology (Software (Data Serialization)))] Decision [|rkyv binary is the single encoded form living both in the database (sema body at rest) and on the wire (component messaging); one AssembledSchema reads bytes in both. NOTA is the text projection at the CLI/inspection edge. Tests prove both boundaries, not only in-memory Rust types.|] VeryHigh High Zero [rkyv nota sema assembled-schema wire-format cli])) (bkcd ([(Technology (Software (Data Serialization))) (Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Decision [|rkyv is the universal wire base for the schema-derived stack; the NOTA codec (NotaDecode/NotaEncode + derive) is opt-in per consumer. DOUBLE clients (text+binary, e.g. CLI) carry the NOTA derive; binary-only clients (daemon) omit it for leanness and to structurally reject NOTA text at the wire. Same data types across consumers — only the derive set differs; byte-compatibility comes from the identical shared rkyv layout. Schema-emitted types derive both NOTA and rkyv from one .asschema, with extra communication traits on roots that cross component boundaries, reusing the same NOTA typed interfaces as direct Rust rather than a parallel mini-codec.|] High VeryHigh Zero [rkyv nota notadecode notaencode asschema schema-rust-next daemon cli])) (hc0t ([(Technology (Software (Data Serialization)))] Constraint [|The assembled schema (.asschema) is canonical NOTA-and-rkyv only, round-tripped through AsschemaNotaWriter/Reader. All NOTA output comes from the typed codec — a printed type label is a real decodable shape, never hand-rolled witness/line formats or ad hoc field joins; a known-root file is its root body encoded through an object/body abstraction over ordered fields.|] VeryHigh Medium Zero [asschema nota rkyv assembled-schema typed-codec])) (ypb5 ([(Technology (Software (Data Serialization)))] Decision [|Spirit record privacy is an Optional field available to any record kind: a public record's privacy is None, an elevated one is (Some Magnitude). Optionality is the explicit None token, never an omitted positional field — every NOTA positional record carries every field.|] High Medium Zero [spirit nota privacy optional])) (3naf ([(Technology (Software (Data Serialization)))] Correction [NOTA encoders avoid over-bracketing: bare-safe atoms encode bare inside typed positions like vectors, bracket forms reserved for whitespace/delimiter safety; typed projection drops redundant wrapper delimiters when the enclosing head already fixes the payload shape, rendering operation-root fields directly.] High Minimum Zero [nota encoding bare-atom])) (4vde ([(Technology (Software (Data Serialization)))] Principle [SEMA is the compact data format defined by schema.] High Minimum Zero [sema schema])) (5fdr ([(Technology (Software (Data Serialization)))] Correction [Signal is NOTA-free: signal-frame and the signal-component / meta-signal-component contract crates carry binary/rkyv only, with no NOTA encoding or projection on request/reply types. NOTA is a separate text-edge concern living outside signal.] High Medium Zero [signal signal-frame signal-component meta-signal-component nota rkyv])) (bexd ([(Technology (Software (Data Serialization)))] Principle [Component feedback, status, and errors are typed self-descriptive NOTA enums and structs whose names carry the meaning — a result type named well enough to need no message string. Our feedback language is enums/structs decoded through NOTA, specializing strings-only-at-the-edges to the messaging surface.] High Medium Zero [nota component-feedback error-reporting])) (h053 ([(Technology (Software (Data Serialization))) (Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Decision [|One typed noun per semantic object across the schema/NOTA stack: source text and checked-in/serialized artifact share the same datatype unless there's a real semantic projection. Assembled schema is one typed Asschema object projected to rkyv bytes (SEMA db), binary archive, and .asschema NOTA text via the same Nota-derived types; a SchemaMacro source entry fits one serializable enum variant, not split source/data enums. Schema source itself is a typed value with a dedicated in/out codec reading strict NOTA source into source-node data and writing it back canonically, distinct from raw NOTA parsing and from assembled serialization.|] High Medium Zero [asschema schema-macro nota rkyv sema schema-source])) (l1ip ([(Technology (Software (Data Serialization)))] Clarification [|A loaded schema file's root struct shape is known a priori from the root KIND (base vs reactive) signaled outside the bytes (extension/load context), like